               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-909" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-909" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-909" type="surname" value="KORTWRIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-909" type="given" value="LAWRENCE"></interp>LAWRENCE KORTWRIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I was an officer in the army. I live in Judd<lb></lb>place—on the afternoon of the 17th of March, I was in High-street, St. Giles—I law some persons assembled, and I stopped for a moment on the pave<lb></lb>ment—the crowd was in the street—I felt something at my pocket—I turned my head round, and saw the prisoner take my handkerchief out of my right<lb></lb>hand coat pocket—he ran off immediately into the crowd—I followed him, and collared him—I said, "Give me my pocket handkerchief"—he said, "I have not got your handkerchief"—I said, "You have got it in your left hand breeches' pocket, and if you don't produce it I will take it out"—he immedi<lb></lb>ately produced it out of his pocket—I gave him in charge.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> This was St. Patrick's-day? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, St. Giles's is the high place of the Irish—there was a quarrel and a fight, I believe—I saw the prisoner's arm, and my handkerchief in his hand—I am sure he took it—I never lost sight of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-910" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-910" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-910" type="surname" value="ATTO"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-910" type="given" value="WILLIAM HUTSON"></interp>WILLIAM HUTSON ATTO</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable E</hi> 120.) I took the prisoner, and received the handkerchief from Mr. Kortwright—I took the prisoner to the station—the handkerchief was stolen from me on the road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You have got the person who stole it from you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, in the next case—I received it from Major Kortwright—I had got the prisoner about 100 yards from the shop when I lost it—he was perfectly sober when I took him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430403-name-911" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-911" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-911" type="surname" value="BARR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430403-name-911" type="given" value="ELLEN"></interp>ELLEN BARR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a widow, and live in Buckeridge-street, I have known the prisoner five years. On St. Patrick's-day I sat in a chair outside my door—I saw the prisoner drunk on the other side of the way, and two young men put their hands under his arms, and drag him across the street—I told them to take him home.</p>
